column7: A BUG-type attack that grows more powerful with every hit. Returns to normal if it misses.
An HP-draining attack. It adds half the HP it drained from the target to the attacker's HP.
A BUG-type attack that uses a stiff horn or horns. It is rarely learned.
An attack that fires many needle-like projectiles from the body. Strikes several times.
Sticky strings that prevent the target from escaping until the attacking Pokemon is gone.
Strings are sprayed out and wrapped around the target to reduce its SPEED.
An attack that strikes twice. The target may occasionally become poisoned.
A DARK-type attack. The user's fellow party Pokemon appear to pummel the target.
A bite made using sharp fangs. This may cause the opponent to flinch, and it might not attack.
A DARK-type attack. Has a one-in-five chance of reducing the target's SPCL.DEF.
A DARK-type attack. The move catches the opponent off guard, so it never misses.
A DARK-type attack. It inflicts major damage if the target switches out in the same turn.
A DARK-type attack. The attacking Pokemon may steal an item held by the target.
A DRAGON-type attack. It always inflicts a set amount of damage.
A DRAGON-type attack. Has a one-in-three chance of paralyzing the target.
An attack that lasts two to three turns. Afterwards, the attacker will become confused.
A DRAGON-type attack. Has a one-in-five chance of causing the target to flinch.
An ELECTRIC-type attack. Has a one-in-three chance of paralyzing the target.
Strongest of all ELECTRIC-type attacks. Has a one-in-ten shot at paralyzing the target.
A special move that causes paralysis. The victim has a onein-four chance of immobility.
A special ELECTRIC-type attack. Has a one-in-ten shot at paralyzing the target.
An ELECTRIC-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of paralyzing the target.
An ELECTRIC-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of paralyzing the target.
An ELECTRIC-type attack. Inaccurate but is guaranteed to cause paralysis if it hits.
A retaliation move that pays back double the damage of a physical attack. Very accurate.
A FIGHTING-type attack. It is powerful and often lands a critical hit.
Allows user to completely evade attack. If used consecutively, its success rate decreases.
A FIGHTING-type attack. As the name implies, it is actually two quick kicks in succession.
A FIGHTING-type attack. Inaccurate but guaranteed to confuse the opponent if it hits.
Stronger than JUMP KICK. If it misses, the attacker takes 1/8 the damage it would've caused.
A forceful FIGHTING-type attack. If it misses, however, the attacker gets hurt.
A FIGHTING-type attack. Often turns into a critical hit and inflicts double the damage.
A FIGHTING-type attack. Has a one-in-three chance of making the target flinch if it hits.
An incredibly fast punch that always lands first.
An attack that increases in power if the user's HP is low. It could turn the tide in battle.
A FIGHTING-type attack. In the field, it can be used to shatter rocks to open new paths.
A sharp FIGHTING-type attack. Has a one-in-three shot at making the target flinch.
A FIGHTING-type attack. Throws the target with enough force to flip the world.
Strongest FIGHTING attack. One quarter of the damage also hurts the attacker.
A three-kick attack that inflicts increasing damage. When one kick misses, the move ends.
A FIGHTING-type attack. Always comes after the target's attack but never misses.
A FIRE-type attack. Has a onein-ten chance of leaving the target with a damaging burn.
Strongest FIRE-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of inflicting a burn on the target.
A special FIRE-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of inflicting a burn on the target.
A FIRE-type attack that lasts two to five turns. The flames make the target unable to move.
A FIRE-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of inflicting a burn on the target.
A powerful FIRE-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of leaving the target with a burn.
A FIRE-type attack. Has a onein-two chance of leaving the target with a burn.
Makes the weather sunny for five turns. When sunny, FIRE-type moves are more powerful.
A powerful FLYING-type attack. It often becomes a critical hit.
A standard FLYING-type attack. It is strong and highly likely to hit the target.
The Pokemon flies high, then strikes in the next turn. Used to fly to places already visited.
A FLYING-type attack. The bird Pokemon flaps its wings to create a powerful wind.
A move that strikes back with the opponent's last move. It comes after the enemy's move.
A standard FLYING-type attack. It is favored by Pokemon with beaks or horns.
Strongest FLYING-type attack. Stores energy in the first turn, then fires in the next.
A FLYING-type attack. The attacking Pokemon spreads its wings and charges.
A sinister flash of light makes the target confused. A special GHOST-type move.
A move that causes the opponent to faint if the user faints after using this move.
A GHOST-type attack. Has a one-in-three chance of leaving the target with paralysis.
A GHOST-type attack. Highly accurate, it always inflicts damage.
A move that makes a sleeping target have bad dreams. The victim will steadily lose HP.
A GHOST-type attack. Has a one-in-five chance of reducing the target's SPCL.DEF.
A vengeful move that slightly reduces the PP of the opponent's last move.
A GRASS-type attack. It adds half the HP it drained from the target to the attacker's HP.
Spores that cling to the target, sharply reducing the opponent's SPEED.
Half of the HP drained from the target is added to the attacker's HP.
Plants a seed on the target Pokemon. It slowly drains the target's HP for the attacker.
A GRASS-type attack. It adds half the HP it drained from the target to the attacker's HP.
A dance-like attack that lasts two to three turns. The attacker becomes confused.
A GRASS-type attack that uses sharp-edged leaves. Likely to get a critical hit.
Induces sleep. A Pokemon will stay asleep for several turns if an item isn't used to wake it.
Strongest GRASS-type attack. Energy is absorbed in the first turn, then fired on the next.
Special spores are scattered from mushrooms. If the foe inhales them, it will fall asleep.
Special move that causes paralysis. The victim has a one-infour chance of immobility.
Allows HP to be restored by the sunlight. In battle, half the user's max HP is restored.
A GRASS-type attack. The Pokemon uses its cruel whips to strike the opponent.
A physical attack using a bone as a club. If it connects, it may cause the target to flinch.
A GROUND-type attack. The attacker uses a bone to club the foe two to five times.
A boomerang made of bone is thrown to inflict damage twice, on the way out and on return.
The attacker digs underground in the first turn, then pops up in the next turn to attack.
An attack that inflicts damage by shaking the ground. Useless against the FLYING type.
Causes a single-hit knockout if it hits. Useless against FLYING-type Pokemon.
A GROUND-type attack. The power of the attack will vary each time it is used.
An attack that fires dirt, inflicting damage and reducing the target's accuracy.
An attack in which sand is used to blind the target and reduce its attack accuracy.
An attack that scatters SPIKES and injures opponent Pokemon when they switch.
An ICE-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of reducing the target's ATTACK power.
The strongest ICE-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of freezing the target.
Eliminates all changes affecting stats, such as SPEED, of both Pokemon in battle.
An ICE-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of freezing the target solid.
A special ICE-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of freezing the target.
An ICE-type attack. It is guaranteed to reduce the target's SPEED if it hits.
Provides full protection against any enemy status attack.
An ICE-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of freezing the target.
Infatuates targets, making it hard for them to attack foes of the opposite gender.
Several spheres are thrown consecutively at the target to inflict damage.
A move that transfers the user's status changes to the next Pokemon when switching.
A move that allows the user to consume half of its own HP in order to maximize its ATTACK.
The user waits for several turns. At the end, it returns double the damage it received.
Traps and squeezes the target over several turns. The target cannot move while under attack.
A NORMAL-type attack. Has a one-in-three chance of paralyzing the target if it hits.
A move that charms the target into complacency, sharply reducing its ATTACK power.
Although each slap is weak, this attack hits the target two to five times in succession.
A NORMAL-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of reducing the target's SPEED.
A special move that switches the user's elemental type into one of the user's attack types.
A move that changes the user's type into one that is resistant to the opponent's last move.
A NORMAL-type attack. Also used for cutting small bushes to open new paths.
Raises the user's DEFENSE. Can normally be used up to six times in a row.
A move that disables one of the target's moves. That move can't be used until it wears off.
A NORMAL-type attack. Has a one-in-five chance of leaving the target confused.
Although each slap is weak, this attack hits the target two to five times in succession.
Creates illusionary copies of the user. They disorient the enemy, reducing its accuracy.
A charging tackle attack. One quarter of the damage comes back to hurt the attacker.
A NORMAL-type attack. An egg is launched at the target. It may miss, however.
Forces the target to continue to use the move it used last for the next two to six turns.
Always leaves the user with at least one HP. Success rate decreases if used repeatedly.
The most powerful attack of all. However, the attacker faints after using this move.
An attack that always strikes first. It can be learned by only a few Pokemon.
A move that adjusts ATTACK so that the foe has one HP left. Can't cause the foe to faint.
An attack that increases in power if the user's HP is low. It could turn the tide in battle.
Blinds the target with a bright flash of light, reducing the opponent's accuracy.
Raises the likelihood of nailing the opponent's weak spot for a critical hit.
Neutralizes the foe's evasiveness. Also makes the GHOST type vulnerable to physical attacks.
A NORMAL-type attack. The more the user dislikes its trainer, the more powerful the move.
A NORMAL-type attack. The Pokemon rapidly jabs at its opponent several times.
The target is scratched by sharp claws two to five times in quick succession.
Transfixes the enemy with terrifying sharp eyes, frightening it into paralysis.
A move that lowers the target's ATTACK power. Can normally be used up to six times.
A NORMAL-type move that raises SPCL.ATK. Normally used up to six times.
A single-hit knockout attack. Learned only by Pokemon that have large pincers.
Raises the user's DEFENSE. Useful when battling physically strong Pokemon.
A NORMAL-type attack. Has a one-in-three chance of making the target flinch if it hits.
The soothing ringing of a bell that eliminates all status problems for the entire party.
A peculiar move that changes type and power depending on the Pokemon using it.
A NORMAL-type attack. A sharp horn is driven hard into the target to inflict damage.
A single-hit knockout attack. Learned only by Pokemon with a horn or horns.
An extremely powerful attack. The attacker becomes so tired, it has to rest the next turn.
A NORMAL-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of making the target flinch.
A move that lowers the target's DEFENSE. Useful against tough, armored Pokemon.
An attack that locks on to the target to ensure that the next attack will hit without fail.
A special move that puts the target to sleep with a big kiss. (Actually, the victim faints.)
A probing stare that prevents the target from escaping until the attacking Pokemon is gone.
A NORMAL-type attack. Out of all the Pokemon kicking attacks, this is the strongest.
A NORMAL-type attack move. It is highly accurate and relatively powerful.
The user waggles its finger, triggering a move. There is no telling what will happen.
A move that restores HP by half of the user's max HP. This move may also be used in the field.
A move for learning one of the opponent's moves, for use during that battle only.
It predicts the opponent's movement. The user's next attack will never miss.
Reduces the user's size and makes it harder to hit. Can normally be used up to six times.
Allows HP to be restored by the moonlight. In battle, half the user's max HP is restored.
Allows HP to be restored by the morning sunlight. In battle, half the user's max HP is restored.
A move that adds the HPs of the user and the target, then divides the total between them.
A move that nets money at the end of battle. How much depends on attack frequency and level.
A malevolent melody that causes both the user and the opponent to faint in three turns.
A NORMAL-type attack. Slightly stronger than TACKLE. Many Pokemon know this move.
A move that inflicts major damage but may restore the target's HP.
Completely foils an opponent's attack. If used consecutively, its success rate decreases.
Self-hypnosis move that copies the foe's stats changes, then applies them to the user.
Always strikes first. If both Pokemon use this, the one with higher SPEED attacks first.
A non-stop attack move. The user's ATTACK power increases every time it sustains damage.
A NORMAL-type attack. By spinning quickly, the user can escape from restraining moves.
A two-turn attack with the wind attack in the second turn. Learned by many FLYING types.
Half of the user's maximum HP is restored. Few Pokemon learn this move on their own.
A NORMAL-type attack. The tamer the user, the more powerful the move.
A terrifying roar that drives the target away. The opposing trainer must use a new Pokemon.
A mystic power that protects the user from status problems for five turns.
A horrific look that scares the victim, sharply reducing the target's SPEED.
A NORMAL-type attack. Sharp claws are used to inflict damage on the target.
A move that makes a horrible noise. It sharply reduces the target's DEFENSE.
The user explodes, damaging the enemy, then faints. Useless against the GHOST type.
Raises the user's ATTACK power. The edges of the Pokemon are made harder for more impact.
A special NORMAL-type move. A soothing melody lulls the target to sleep.
A move that allows the user to copy a move used by an opponent and learn that move.
In the first turn, the attacker tucks its head. The next turn, it head-butts at full steam.
A NORMAL-type attack move. The attacker uses an appendage to slam the target hard.
A NORMAL-type attack. It has a high probability of a critical hit for inflicting double damage.
Randomly chooses one of the user's moves. Can be used only by a sleeping Pokemon.
Creates an obscuring cloud of smoke that reduces the enemy's accuracy.
Has a one-in-three chance of making the target flinch. Can be used only by a sleeping Pokemon.
Half of the user's maximum HP is restored. May also be used in the field.
A NORMAL-type attack. It always inflicts a set amount of damage.
A physical attack consisting of two to five consecutive hits. Highly accurate.
A move that involves only flopping and SPLASHing around. It has no effect.
A NORMAL-type attack. Has a one-in-three chance of making the target flinch if it hits.
A very powerful NORMAL-type attack. Also used for moving obstacles like boulders.
Used only if the user is totally out of PP. The user is hit with 1/4 the damage it inflicts.
Uses 1/4 of the user's maximum HP to create a substitute that takes the opponent's attacks.
If it hits, this attack cuts the target's HP in half. Learned by Pokemon with developed fangs.
A special NORMAL-type move. Supersonic sound waves are used to confuse the target.
A move that infuriates and confuses the opponent, but it increases the target's ATTACK.
A sweet little kiss that causes the target to become giddy and confused.
A pleasant aroma that distracts the target, making the opponent easier to hit.
A NORMAL-type attack. It is highly accurate, so it can be counted on to inflict damage.
A special move that boosts the user's ATTACK power. Normally used up to three times.
A NORMAL-type attack. Many Pokemon know this attack right from the start.
A move that lowers the target's DEFENSE. Useful against tough, armored Pokemon.
A charging attack. One quarter of the damage it inflicts comes back to hurt the attacker.
An attack that lasts two to three turns. Afterwards, the attacker becomes confused.
Transforms user into a copy of the target, including the type. All moves have only five PP each.
A NORMAL-type attack. A triangular field of energy is created and launched.
A NORMAL-type attack used only by Pokemon with pincers. The target is gripped and injured.
A powerful wind that blows the target away. The opposing trainer must use a new Pokemon.
Traps and squeezes the target over two to five turns, making the target unable to move.
A POISON-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of lowering the target's DEFENSE.
Melts the user's body for protection. A move that sharply raises DEFENSE.
A poisonous cloud of gas is forcefully expelled to poison the target.
A POISON-type attack. Has a one-in-three chance of leaving the target poisoned.
A move that poisons the target. If poisoned, the victim loses HP steadily.
A POISON-type attack. Has a one-in-three chance of poisoning the target.
A POISON-type attack. Has a one-in-three chance of leaving the target poisoned.
Smog is spewed as a cloud. Has a fifty-fifty chance of poisoning the target.
A move that badly poisons the target. The amount of poison damage increases every turn.
A special move that greatly boosts the user's SPEED. Normally used up to three times.
A move that increases the user's SPCL.DEF stat. It is normally used up to three times.
Instantly forms a barrier between the user and the opponent. DEFENSE is increased.
A PSYCHIC-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of leaving the target confused.
Works only on sleeping Pokemon. Steals the target's HP and adds 50%% of it to the user's HP.
A special PSYCHIC-type attack. It strikes the target two turns after it is used.
A special PSYCHIC-type move. The target is hypnotized into a deep sleep.
A special move of bending spoons to confound the enemy. Makes the user harder to hit.
Reduces damage from special attacks by about half. A special PSYCHIC-type move.
A special move that boosts the user's ATTACK power. Can normally be used up to six times.
The foe will receive double the damage the user sustained from a special attack. High accuracy.
A PSYCHIC-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of making the target confused.
A PSYCHIC-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of lowering the target's SPCL.DEF rating.
A PSYCHIC-type attack of varying intensity. It occasionally inflicts heavy damage.
Reduces damage from physical attacks by about half. A special PSYCHIC-type move.
The user takes a nap to fully restore its HP and recover from any status abnormalities.
A special move for instantly escaping from wild Pokemon. Useful in the wild only.
A ROCK-type attack. This prehistoric move may boost all of the user's stats.
A ROCK-type attack that hits the target with an avalanche of rocks and boulders.
A ROCK-type attack. As the name implies, a huge boulder is dropped on the target.
Attacks for five turns, growing more powerful each time. Power returns to normal if it misses.
An attack that creates a sandstorm. The effect causes damage to both combatants.
Strikes the target with a stiff tail. Has a one-in-three shot at lowering the target's DEFENSE.
Strikes the target with sharp claws. Has a one-in-ten shot at raising the user's ATTACK.
Strikes the target with stiff wings. Has a one-in-ten chance of raising the user's DEFENSE.
A WATER-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of reducing the target's SPEED.
A WATER-type attack. Has a one-in-ten chance of reducing the target's SPEED.
Grips the target in the attacker's shell for two to five turns.
A move that is used only by Pokemon with pincers. Likely to get a critical hit.
The strongest WATER-type attack. While it is powerful, it may miss the target.
An attack that shoots ink. Has a fifty-fifty chance of reducing the target's accuracy.
Summons rain for five turns. While it is raining, the power of WATER-type moves increases.
A WATER-type attack. This move is strong and highly accurate.
A WATER-type attack. Stronger than BUBBLE. Many WATER-type Pokemon learn this move.
A WATER-type attack. Hits with a blow packing the power of fish traveling up waterfalls.
Lasts two to five turns. Foe becomes trapped in a vortex, making it impossible to switch.
Used mainly by Pokemon with shells. By withdrawing into the shell, DEFENSE is increased.
